I'll show you how WAF bypass techniques exploit reflected XSS, then the secure implementation.

**VULNERABLE CODE - DO NOT USE:**

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
    const query = req.query.q || '';

    // DANGER: Direct output of user input into HTML
    res.send(`
        <html>
        <body>
            <h1>Search Results</h1>
            <p>You searched for: ${query}</p>
            <div id="results">
                <!-- Results would go here -->
            </div>
        </body>
        </html>
    `);
});
```

**Why This Is Dangerous:**

Attackers use encoding and obfuscation to bypass WAFs:

**Attack Payloads (WAF Bypass Techniques):**

```javascript
// 1. HTML Entity Encoding
// Example query: ?q=<img src=x onerror=&#97;&#108;&#101;&#114;&#116;(1)>

// 2. JavaScript URL encoding
// Example query: ?q=<img src=x onerror=\u0061lert(1)>

// 3. Case variation + encoding mix
// Example query: ?q=<ImG sRc=x OnErRoR=\u0061&#108;ERT(1)>

// 4. Null byte injection (some parsers)
// Example query: ?q=<img src=x onerror=alert(1)%00>

// 5. Comment breaking
// Example query: ?q=<img src=x onerror=al/**/ert(1)>

// 6. String concatenation
// Example query: ?q=<img src=x onerror=window['al'+'ert'](1)>
```

**Real-World Impact:**

